<TEXT>
for 20 years stories have been told in ethiopia 
about two white children kidnapped or abandoned when they were very 
young a brother and sister have stepped forward claiming to be 
those children nairobi bureau chief reid g miller wrote about the 
two earlier this month and here is a followup report 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a young man and woman who may be the 
legendary lost white children of ethiopia say they have a 
sister and they introduced her during a visit to the us embassy 
all three arrived at the embassy last week for an interview with 
consul richard adams in an effort to find their parents 
they say they were taken from a white family about 20 years ago 
by the ethiopian housekeeper whose sister and brotherinlaw raised 
them as members of the oromo tribe the story of two lost white 
children is told in many variations usually involving a kidnapping 
a representative of the international rescue committee in new 
york has come to addis ababa in hopes of taking all three to the 
united states 
we are prepared to arrange transportation care and education 
for them in the states said ron laytner an author and freelance 
journalist from fort lauderdale fla 
laytner and adams say that may be difficult because haile mariam 
gadessa and his sisters tegest and lesa are at least for now 
considered to be ethiopian nationals 
anything we do will be legal said laytner who carried a 
letter from former us ambassador angier biddle duke a committee 
director identifying him as its representative 
the international rescue committee is a nonpartisan agency to 
assist resettle rehabilitate refugees it is supported by 
foundations corporations unions community groups and individual 
contributors 
haile mariam and tegest came to the attention of us officials 
when an ethiopian friend took them to the embassy in june 
in their interview with consul carol l rose who retired earlier 
this month they did not mention their sister lesa fearing for 
her safety they say now 
meeting with the new consul last week the three told essentially 
the same story haile mariam and tegest related to mrs rose through 
an interpreter two months ago 
it was adams first meeting with the young people thought to be 
in their early 20s an associated press reporter was allowed to 
attend the twohour interview 
they say they have no clear recollection of their real parents 
but spoke for the first time of seeing a photo album in the 
grassthatched mud hut that became their home 
pictures in the album showed them as small children with their 
white parents they said haile mariam said fire destroyed the hut 
and photos years ago 
they say they dont know for sure why they were taken to live 
with the tribal couple they believe their father became ill and had 
to be evacauated and that their mother went with him 
mrs rose adams and others think the story of the lost white 
children may have been kept alive by occasional sightings of haile 
mariam and lesa they were kept by the oromo couple and tegest was 
sent to another family as a maid 
the embassy has found no record of the youngsters or their 
parents but adams said a few vague clues arose after their story 
came to light 
adams and an ethiopian lawyer hired by the embassy are trying to 
run down the clues he said one was a tip in a letter mailed from 
addis ababa that the father had been a brewery chemist in addis 
ababa 
as a result of the article people sent cash checks and offers 
of help to the embassy 
initially we discouraged people from sending money because 
unless these people are us citizens we would have no authority to 
set up a trust account for them adams said 
later he said the state department suggested establishing an 
account through someone not connected with the us government 
we would like to try to set up an account through a benign 
person here a missionary or somebody he said there is 
significant interest in this serious interest at the state 
department 
the oromo woman who raised the three recalls her brother bringing 
them to her and denied they were kidnapped but was vague about 
brothers motives she said he died soon afterward 
they were beautiful children very white she told reporters 
through an interpreter at her farm 50 miles from addis ababa she is 
in her 70s and divorced 
although they carry her last name the youngsters bear no 
resemblance to the black woman who raised them their hair is light 
brown to blond their complexions a ruddy bronze 
they tell of a lifetime of physical abuse by their foster father 
and other villagers because of their strange appearance 
adams ended the interview when they became agitated the 
interpreter said they were tired of retelling their story to 
consular officers and reporters without result and frightened by 
the increased hostility of fellow villagers caused by their 
notoriety 
the bbc overseas service broadcast their story in amharic 
ethiopias official language and many ethiopians heard it 
because of what the interpreter said adams took up an office 
collection to rent a small apartment in the capital for a month he 
had the young people resettled and urged them to return to the 
embassy for more conversations 
if only we can jog their memories enough we may be able to 
find further clues to their identities and their parents he said 
just before the meeting with adams ended haile mariam said 
our thought is that if our parents are dead why havent our 
grandparents aunts or uncles come looking for us this is what we 
always think this is what we dont understand 
</TEXT>
