<TEXT>
prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki a symbol 
of the astounding change in the communist world has emerged as a 
cautious conciliatory negotiator who admits he is frightened by the 
challenge ahead 
a lot of things terrify me he said as he paused after his 
nomination last week to contemplate his momentous mission 
the first noncommunist prime minister to head an east bloc 
government mazowiecki faces awesome responsibility 
he must negotiate the competing demands of factions long at 
ideological odds while confronting economic disaster and inspiring a 
populace that has exhausted its faith in government of any stripe 
at first i felt as if someone had put 100 kilos of stones on my 
head mazowiecki said but i calmed down and started looking 
with a certain optimism otherwise i could not take on this role 
mazowiecki was proposed as the head of a governing coalition by 
solidarity leader lech walesa for whom mazowiecki has been a close 
adviser since the founding of the independent union during shipyard 
strikes in 1980 
the 62yearold lawyer and journalist a lifelong anticommunist 
with close ties to the roman catholic church was not among the most 
public solidarity leaders nothing could have prepared him for the 
hopes now centered on him 
he has responded with remarkable calm there have been no fiery 
speeches nor radical announcements his diplomacy may smooth the 
delicate transition or it may disappoint those waiting to be 
ignited 
although his demeanor has been mild those who know him say he 
can be tough 
mazowieckis solidarity activism earned him a year in prison 
after the martiallaw crackdown imposed in 1981 by wojciech 
jaruzelski the communist president who nominated him as prime 
minister saturday 
but associates say he was not embittered his approach to the 
weakened but still crucial communist party so far has been to play 
down differences and offer compromise there has been little sense 
of triumph 
i think we should be mutually open to each other and aim at a 
situation where no reluctance and aggression take place between us 
because what poland needs now is a joint effort of all forces he 
said after hearing of a sharply worded resolution from the party 
to the polish people he has offered a mix of hope and realism 
asking them to believe that it can be better in this country 
while acknowledging society has no concept how difficult it will 
be to reform this economy 
graying and dignified mazowiecki appears solemn serious and 
even cool but he has shown humor and a human side during the tense 
week joking about running out of gas while driving not fitting 
for a premier and craving a cigarette away from the cameras 
the widowed father of three sons who has four grandchildren 
mazowiecki was editing solidaritys weekly newspaper when history 
turned to him he had founded the newspaper during the unions first 
legal months in 1980 and resurrected it when solidarity was 
legalized again in april 
walesa had entrusted him with a major role in the negotiations 
between the opposition and the communist authorities that led to 
restoration of solidaritys legal status and the freest parliament 
elections in postwar poland he was in charge of the talks on trade 
union issues 
this spring mazowiecki chose to remain an editor rather than run 
for the national assembly 
he had been a sejm deputy from 1961 to 1970 as a member of znak 
an officially condoned delegation under the churchs protection that 
supported regeneration of poland based on catholic values 
in 1971 when he tried unsuccessfully to establish a sejm 
commission to study the violent repression of strikes that swept the 
baltic coast following price increases in december 1970 he 
overstepped official tolerance and was denied another term 
born april 18 1927 to an intelligentsia family in the small 
central poland city of plock mazowiecki attended warsaw university 
by age 21 in the early years of communist poland he was dismissed 
from his academic editing house job for links too close to the 
church 
he began to work for pax set up by the government to dilute 
churchbased opposition but one of the few venues for independent 
thought by 1955 he had been dismissed for criticizing the mix of 
politics and religion 
in 1958 he founded the wiez or link a progressive catholic 
monthly magazine that he edited until 1981 
the warsaw club of catholic intelligentsia he helped found in 
1957 became the core of the catholic fight against to communist 
ideology 
on aug 22 1980 he arrived at the strikebound lenin shipyard 
and after a nightlong session with walesa he took charge of a group 
of experts advising the workers on organizing the union 
he stayed with walesa and the movement through seven years of 
resistance 
in the council of minister building during his first hours as 
prime minister he recalled walking out of the lenin shipyard with 
workers in disappoinment after an unfruitful occupation strike in 
may 1988 
i think that neither them nor i thought that exit would lead to 
my entrance here today he said 
</TEXT>
