this years lingering drought in major wheat 
areas continues to drain us grain reserves and push up market 
prices the agriculture department says in a new analysis 
moreover the departments economic research service said 
thursday world stockpiles are in similar shape with wheat reserves 
the lowest since the mid1970s 
the analysis was based on the aug 10 estimate that wheat 
production would be about 204 billion bushels up 13 percent from 
the 1988 harvest 
wheat use including exports is expected to be 229 billion 
bushels in the marketing year that began june 1 down 5 percent from 
198889 
with us farm prices expected near the target price 4 per 
bushel in 198990 and increased competitor supplies exports may 
decline more than 10 percent to less than 13 billion bushels the 
report said the us share of world trade is expected to slip as 
well 
at the end of the 198889 wheat marketing year the united states 
had about 694 million bushels from previous harvests in its 
stockpile and this june 1 carryover was down from more than 
126 billion bushels a year earlier 
by next june 1 the report said the wheat stockpile will be 
trimmed further to an estimated 474 million bushels down more than 
30 percent and the smallest carryover since 197475 
most of the reduction will occur in the inventories held by the 
departments commodity credit corp as forfeited collateral for 
price support loans made to producers other reductions will be in 
the farmerowned reserve of wheat stored under loan and released 
to the market as prices rise and the loans become due 
area planted increased 17 percent in response to attractive 
prices and less acreage idled under annual government programs but 
yields are forecast to be the lowest since 1978 because of 
lingering drought in major wheat production areas the report said 
because of the continued tight wheat supply the government has 
lowered the landidling requirement for 1990 to 5 percent of the 
base acreage down from 10 percent for 1989 and 275 percent in 
1988 that is land farmers must take from production to qualify for 
federal supports 
wheat prices are projected to average in the range of 385 to 
425 per bushel in the 198990 marketing year up from 372 
estimated for 198889 
the global wheat situation is similar to the us the report 
said world production is forecast up 265 million tons to 527 
million metric tons in 198990 however consumption is expected to 
outpace production for the third consecutive year reducing stocks 
to their lowest since 197576 
relatively high export prices are expected but world demand 
for imported wheat is likely to remain strong the report said 
