<TEXT>
the antiaids drug azt apparently stays in the 
body longer when combined with a drug commonly used to treat gout 
allowing patients to use less of it researchers said friday 
if further tests continue to show the combination of azt and the 
drug probenecid is safe and effective aids patients may be able to 
significantly reduce azt dosages said dr david m kornhauser 
assistant professor of medicine at johns hopkins division of 
clinical phamacology 
kornhauser said the combination therapy could lead to a major 
reduction in the skyrocketing cost of aids treatment 
the national institute of allergy and infectious disease reported 
last week that azt delays the progession of aids in some 
hivinfected people who have not developed aids symptoms a group 
estimated at up to 630000 nationwide 
at the current cost of up to 8000 annually per patient for azt 
also known as azidothymidine treating this group with the drug 
could reach more than 5 billion yearly kornhauser said that cost 
could be cut in half with the combination therapy 
the hopkins study conducted during the first six months of 1988 
was published in fridays edition of the british medical journal 
lancet 
at this time were not saying that everyone should go out and 
use probenecid kornhauser said this is an important first 
step but we must continue with careful study before this therapy is 
widely adopted 
i think we should proceed to see if the combination works as 
well as azt alone because it would make it a therapy less expensive 
for patients and less expensive for the country kornhauser added 
probenecid apparently works by slowing the combination of 
flucuronic acid a sugar derivative with azt 
hopkins researchers gave the aztprobenecid combination to eight 
men with either aids or aidsrelated complex for three days and then 
measured azt concentrations in the blood they found that levels of 
azt were nearly doubled by adding probenecid so that patients might 
be able to take the drug once every eight hours instead of the usual 
four hours 
a second monthlong trial of eight to 10 people less ill than 
those in the initial study is expected to begin within the next two 
weeks 
well be studying this group to see how well they tolerate the 
combination over a longer period of time while looking for signs of 
toxicity which we dont anticipate kornhauser said 
he said the next step would be a trial involving at least 1000 
aids patients to compare the use of azt alone with the combination 
treatment 
