<TEXT>
state election officials said friday they face 
financial and other obstacles in trying to implement voluntary 
federal guidelines for computerized voting systems 
the federal election commission standards intended to guide 
state authorities who oversee elections are aimed at assuring that 
the computerized systems used in many states are accurate and 
fraudfree but a draft proposal has come under criticism from some 
public interest groups 
the state election officials voiced their concerns at a meeting 
of the 20member advisory panel of the fecs national clearinghouse 
on election administration 
ronald michaelson executive director of the illinois state board 
of elections said he expects that implementing the fec standards 
will require very arduous efforts 
i anticipate its going to be a very difficult task in 
illinois and a timeconsuming one he said 
dot joyce a florida election official said her states 
legislature last january passed legislation largely modeled after 
the fec standards which have been in the drafting stage for several 
years but provided no money for carrying it out 
since then she said weve just been really scratching our 
heads picking peoples brains weve been operating with no 
funds to put our standards in place 
deborah seiler californias chief of elections and political 
reform said election authorities in her state also lack enough 
money to implement the computerized voting system standards 
we will need funds to help us adopt that part of the 
standards which involves the certification process for computer 
equipment and software she said 
penelope bonsall director of the fec clearinghouse told the 
meeting the commission aims to make a final decision on the 
standards by late october she said that a 30day period for 
submitting public comments on the standards will run through sept 8 
public interest groups criticizing the draft standards include 
election watch a project of the urban policy research institute 
based in pacific palisades calif 
the first major inadequacy is that theyre not mandatory 
said mae churchill director of election watch the second is that 
there was virtually no sign of any public input into their 
creation 
there has been increased concern in recent years over the 
accuracy and security of computerized tabulation systems which in 
1988 were used in handling more than 50 percent of all voters 
ballots nationwide 
the election community is underfunded and underorganized 
according to lance j hoffman a computer science professor at 
george washington university with some exceptions it knows 
little about managing computer security few jurisdictions share 
knowledge therefore american elections are more vulnerable to 
fraud and error than is desirable or necessary 
the proposed fec standards outline in technical language the 
steps that should be followed by election authorities to operate a 
reliable voting system the latest draft was released aug 8 
the standards are to be voluntary because by law states control 
their own election systems computerized voting systems include 
those using punchcards marksense cards in which a person marks his 
choice in pencil on cards that are read by computer and 
directrecording electronic systems in which the voter pushes a 
button 
