the agencys new director harry m snyder suspended the ruling 
that cleared the way for belville coal co to apply for state mining 
permits on governmentprotected land in the wayne national forest 
the entire matter is on hold said snyder who wants the 
paperwork refiled and the procedures leading up the controversial 
decision repeated 
the critical issue is making sure fair and open procedures are 
followed in reaching a decision he said in a prepared statement 
in a letter to the coal company the ohio department of natural 
resources and the us forest service which opposes mining in the 
southern ohio forest snyder said indications exist that osm may 
not have followed its own internal procedures 
that same charge was leveled in june by rep nick rahall dwva 
investigators for the house mining subcommittee which rahall 
heads concluded the interior department agency failed to get 
independent documentation and skimpily reviewed company documents 
before deciding belville had a valid right to mine for coal in the 
national forest 
rahall asked the agency to freeze action on all pending coal 
rights claims until the interior department finishes the lengthy 
process of putting a federal standard in place 
snyder didnt respond to that request and the decision he 
announced friday applied only to the ohio case 
snyder said his action came as a result of his review of the 
overall issue of mining rights on protected land and stressed that 
it doesnt necessarily mean the ohio ruling will be changed 
in a reversal of a 1986 decision ironton ohiobased belville in 
december received a crucial bureaucratic approval saying it had the 
right to strip mine for coal on 5440 acres of the national forest 
so far the company has applied for state mining permits covering 
about 180 of those acres but the permits had not been yet been 
issued 
the forest service owns surface rights and manages the 
190000acre wayne national forest and vigorously opposes belvilles 
proposal 
it argues that the federal government should have followed state 
standards since theres no federal standard to apply when companies 
buy previous owners mineral rights and seek to mine on 
governmentprotected land 
the forest service also claimed the mineral rights belville 
bought in 1983 and 1984 do not specify coal mining but instead 
cover the stripmining of fire clay and any coal incidental to the 
claymining fire clay is used in brick making 
</TEXT>
