<TEXT>
ray horne cursed the smoothasglass water in a 
35acre pothole on his farm even though he knew it made a rich 
wildlife breeding area 
that depression does no good for me except it might raise a 
pair of ducks he said as a farmer its no good for me 
horne wont be draining this wetland even though he has all the 
permits he needs instead next winter hell haul dirt onto the 
icecovered pond so when spring arrives mounds will sprout to 
produce ideal nesting habitat for ducks 
hornes change of heart comes at a price he and some neighbors 
are negotiating an agreement with the us fish and wildlife service 
that could pay them up to 40 an acre to raise ducks 
their willingness to negotiate officials say represents a real 
breakthrough in relations that could end the wetlands war north 
dakotas most controversial environmental issue 
the signal i think is that wildlife is able to sit down at 
the table not demanding that every wetland be preserved and 
agriculture is saying we dont want to drain and are willing to 
save some said lloyd jones state game and fish commissioner and 
former director of wetlands habitat for the fish and wildlife 
service that is something that didnt happen in the history of 
north dakota and is happening now 
unlike other states north dakota does not have serious problems 
with dirty water and air in fact other than draining wetlands the 
biggest environmental concern looming for the state is how to get 
rid of its garbage 
the wetlands war has pitted landowners against wildlife 
interests but the ramifications move the issue closer to urban 
consumers by affecting the quality of the wildlife habitat and water 
available for outdoor recreation 
before settlers pushed onto the prairie north dakota had 5 
million acres of wetlands marshy land teeming with wildlife just 2 
million acres remain jones said and he is determined to preserve 
them 
we are seeing a lot of things go wrong with 2 million acres and 
we cant get by with anything less he said 
wetlands act as a natural filter concentrating fertilizer and 
other runoff then releasing more polluted water into lakes and 
streams draining the bowllike indentations dotting the prairie in 
eastern north dakota has disrupted the areas hydrology and removed 
natural storage tanks increasing the chances of flooding jones 
said it also removed natural habitat for ducks and geese 
the drainage was spurred by farmers desire to plant on some of 
their most fertile soil the federal government even paid them at 
one time to drain their sloughs there was a strong public 
attitude that wetlands were wastelands jones said through the 
1970s farmers drained about 20000 acres a year 
by 1987 the legislature passed a law requiring that each acre 
drained had to be replaced the socalled nonetloss policy which 
took effect july 1 
i am real optimistic that the future for wetlands has never 
been better in north dakota jones said people are getting 
along a lot better now people trust each other a lot more now 
not everyone shares that optimism 
i dont know if there is a final solution said ramsey county 
commissioner lloyd stromme landowners in his area remain unhappy 
with the nonetloss law and want it repealed they are disgusted 
that the federal government obtains land without paying full taxes 
on it he sid 
state rep gordon berg whose critics call him mr draino 
for his support of wetland drainage says landowners must be paid 
for their potholes if you dont have the cooperation of the 
farmer youve got nothing 
mike mcenroe of the fish and wildlife service has been 
negotiating with horne and 29 other landowners for preservation of 
1500 acres of wetlands in return for payments of 15 to 40 an 
acre the exact amounts are still being discussed but an agreement 
could be signed within two months he said 
rather than fight with people we figured we would be much 
better off working toward the middle ground mcenroe said we 
are going kind of slow on this one because we want to find out how 
much it costs if it will work up here on a draining project of this 
size i think it can work anywhere 
horne driving around his land northwest of devils lake said the 
roads and trees have disrupted wetlands as much as draining 
potholes his agreement with the government will let him drain some 
of the smaller sloughs in return for preserving and enhancing the 
larger more valuable ones 
ill be your local inhouse manager and we will raise birds or 
whatever he said but i want to get paid for it 
</TEXT>
