<TEXT>
whatever else happens in the stock market over 
the next few months 1989 will go into the history books as the year 
the airlines took wing on wall street 
takeover bids for the parent companies of northwest and united 
have played a large part in transforming an industry long spurned by 
many investors into one of the hottest stock groups around 
that helped dow joness average of 20 transportation stocks reach 
new peaks weeks before the 30stock industrial average did so last 
week 
but theres more to the story than that and with all its 
positive and profitable moments some analysts say it could still 
have an unhappy ending 
nobody disputes that solid business reasons exist for the air 
transport industrys newfound popularity 
traffic fares and profits are up for most major carriers the 
era of bitter price competition that followed airline deregulation 
in the late 1970s appears to be over 
from its competitors point of view the strike that began in 
march at eastern airlines has made a bright situation even 
brighter observed the value line investment survey in its latest 
quarterly report on the group 
pulling easterns 6 percent capacity out of the system has 
produced a very favorable environment for raising airline fares 
wrote value line analyst paul graham 
airline stock enthusiasts cite several other pluses many 
airlines are described as better managed now than they used to be 
and the use of lease financing enables them to expand and modernize 
their fleets much more easily 
on top of all that the carriers have come to be seen as 
attractive to lenders and investors for the assets they own 
thats where some skeptics begin to voice their reservations 
about all the bidding and borrowing that has been taking place 
an airline is simply the wrong kind of company to qualify as a 
good candidate for a buyout financed with debt argues james grant 
in his newsletter grants interest rate observer 
airlines have heavy capitalspending requirements and unions to 
deal with and their business has always been very sensitive to the 
ups and downs of the economy 
every airline is a prisoner of the business cycle and a hostage 
to the price of fuel grant says 
we see in the airline liftoff yet another example of debt in 
action making the good times better and casting a shadow over the 
future we suspect that easy credit will sooner or later give way to 
hard or inaccessible credit 
adds graham at value line were concerned about the value 
being placed on these airline properties 
interest expense for example on borrowings to finance the nwa 
buyout will basically wipe out the carriers earnings in 1990 
thats not an encouraging performance in the strong operating 
environment were forecasting for next year 
in a recession if one of these debtladen carriers were to 
stumble badly we fear it could get quite messy 
moreover much of the alleged asset value in an airline eg 
lucrative route franchises can normally only be tapped by breaking 
up the company few unions will sit idly by while the dismantling is 
taking place 
we think airline stock performance will be very volatile in the 
next several months graham concluded accordingly we advise 
conservative investors to take refuge on the sidelines with those 
individuals who dont buy the airlinemerger story 
