<TEXT>
the greenwood sc school district has spent 90000 to install 
intercoms and a fence around an elementary school where an intruder 
last year shot and killed two thirdgraders and wounded seven other 
students and two teachers 
weapons drugrelated violence thefts and gang problems have 
spread to smalltown schools leading authorities to try the same 
hightech security hardware innercity schools rely on a 50state 
associated press survey has found 
we have to be conscious of security in small districts a lot 
more than we used to be said superintendent luis montoya in 
clifton ariz where a rash of breakins forced the district to 
triple its security outlays in the last five years 
the effort is mainly to protect new vcrs computers tape 
recorders and camera equipment another problem is siphoning of 
gasoline from school buses 
in central michigan the mason school district spends about 
3000 a year on motion detector equipment to protect computers at 
the middle and high schools 
compared to five years ago we didnt have that kind of 
equipment we didnt have that volume of computer equipment to 
protect said superintendent glenn doran 
the 1900student perryton independent school district in the 
texas panhandle pays about 5000 a year for drugsniffing dogs and 
250 for security lighting so far those measures havent turned up 
much spokesman randy barnes acknowledged 
we found a pill once that looked pretty suspicious but it 
turned out to be a contac capsule he said 
in yankton sd school authorities prefer a hard line on school 
crime to security hardware 
a 15yearold boy convicted of making a false bomb threat wound 
up serving time at the state training school and an 18yearold was 
sentenced to one year in the yankton detention center for a similar 
threat 
not every rural school is worried 
several years ago in an incident that drew national attention 
an armed gunman took an entire school of children hostage in 
cokeville wyo but state superintendent lynn simons said the 
incident was an aberration and it didnt change his approach to 
security 
we can rest easy in wyoming we just dont have to worry about 
those problems said simons 
in eatonville wash high school principal randy dorn knows his 
kids sometimes bring weapons to school but he says its only 
during hunting season 
