are examining boxes of documents provided by the exchanges and 
traders defense lawyers said thursday no action in the federal 
probe is expected for at least two months lawyers said 
the official familiar with the criminal probe said investigators 
from the manhattan us attorneys office and the us postal 
service are examining documents subpoenaed by the cftc 
weve still got a while to go on the criminal case the 
official said 
comex spokesman robert mcgrath said semel was fined 350000 and 
suspended for nine months from the exchange while semel amp co was 
fined 200000 
the violations by semel involve improper crosstrading and 
prohibited dual trading two offenses that center on trading for 
customers and personal accounts 
semel 39 and his firm also were cited under exchange rules for 
misconduct disreputable or fraudulent conduct and conduct 
detrimental to the exchange 
comex guidelines regarding the two stated trading violations bar 
traders from taking the opposite side of an order received and from 
trading for personal accounts while holding a customers order for 
the same commodity 
officials said the charges listed generally involve a practice 
know as frontrunning getting an unfair advantage by trading 
for personal accounts ahead of customer orders for the same 
commodity that pracice is under scrutiny in the federal probes 
a person answering the telephone thursday at semel amp co said no 
one would be available for comment 
the cftc probe reportedly examines violations including 
prearranged trading using advance knowledge of customer trades to 
trade for personal accounts and conducting trades in order to skirt 
tax obligations 
the criminal probe reportedly includes examination of alleged 
frontrunning at the exchanges and whether brokers and traders 
illegally shared information with each other about customer orders 
comex issued a complaint against semel a powerful figure on the 
exchange floor in june 1988 for trading that took place before 
then mcgrath said he refused to release other details about the 
internal probe 
semel was expected to appeal the penalty to the cftc but 
spokeswoman kate hathaway said he had not yet done so 
in addition to the comex the government in may issued subpoenas 
to the new york mercantile exchange the coffee sugar and cocoa 
exchange and the cotton exchange 
