experience to go directly into their fields especially in 
computerrelated work said andreas mausch spokesman for the 
federal labor ministry in bonn 
but in the long term with some additional training the 
outlook is very good he said these people want to stay here 
and build careers 
mausch said there were more than 255000 jobs open in bluecollar 
fields that employers had called in to state employment offices 
obviously there are a great many others that we dont even know 
about he said 
signs offering waitress or janitorial work can be seen in the 
windows of shops in virtually every west german city as even young 
west germans resist jobs that are menial or lowpaying 
the nations 2 million jobless more than 8 percent are mostly 
skilled workers in depressed fields such as steelmaking 
shipbuilding and coal mining and the generous social welfare system 
discourages them from switching to other trades 
mausch said east germans with experience in electrical work 
engineering and personal services such as hairdressing were in high 
demand in west germany 
workers in all fields are in severe shortage in east germany 
which has encouraged the communist leadership to retain tight 
restrictions on western travel and emigration despite widespread 
public pressure for reform 
many of the schoeppingen refugees who stay here an average of 
three or four days before setting out for resettlement said they 
left illegally because they knew they would never be allowed to 
emigrate 
we are exactly the kind of people the state doesnt want to 
leave observed one woman who did not want her name used smiling 
sardonically she nodded toward the crush of young families and 
added this must really be killing the authorities at home 
