<TEXT>
when engineering graduate david kimbrell 
looked around in the mid1980s and wondered how to make a living he 
found the answer buried in the walls 
along with colleague frank hall kimbrell founded one of the 
first consulting firms that advise the best way to test for and 
dispose of asbestos the widely used building insulation that has 
been found to cause cancer 
then kimbrell had a hunch about schools 
by the time congress approved a 1986 law requiring control and 
cleanup of asbestos in school buildings kimbrell already had a 
national marketing campaign ready 
hallkimbrells growth exploded its revenues tripling over the 
past three years from contracts with 15 percent of the nations 
school districts 
i dont know if its a sixth sense or what but we kind of feel 
things coming said kimbrell 38 we try to watch for the 
regulatory trends whats the research on what is toxic what are 
the liability issues and we felt that asbestos was going to be a 
major problem 
now kimbrell is betting on his sixth sense again 
we started watching japan two or three years ago he said 
and we speculated that they were just at that stage of 
industrialization where theyre starting to address the issues of 
asbestos and employee occupational exposure so far weve been 
right 
kimbrell bought out halls interest in the firm after the first 
few months of business although hes retained the hallkimbrell 
corporate name 
his hunches have propelled hallkimbrells growth since he and 
his wife drew up a fiveyear plan in 1983 for the company theyd 
started in mississippi the year before theyd already made 120000 
from asbestos consulting and were trying to decide what to do 
we wanted to be the best environmental engineering firm in the 
nation he said we decided to take the specialty we knew 
asbestos and form a national company on that so we drew up a plan 
to take literally every penny we made and put it back into growth 
the plague of lingering asbestos resurfaced this past week when 
federal prosecutors filed civil suits against several defendants 
nationwide alleging improper handling of the material during 
renovation and removal projects the lawsuits underscored the 
importance of the kind of services that hallkimbrell and other 
asbestoscleansing consultants provide 
hallkimbrell has surveyed more than 1300 school districts for 
asbestos in addition to 15 state governments 200 colleges ten 
airports and thousands of commercial clients typically its 
engineers develop a plan to remove or contain asbestos then monitor 
another company that actually does the work 
its revenues grew from 248000 in 1983 to 45 million last year 
and a 34th place on inc magazines list of the fastestgrowing us 
companies 
the firm now employs about 800 people in 26 offices 
hallkimbrell moved to lawrence near kansas city to be in the 
central part of the country and near a regional environmental 
protection agency office but much of its work remains on the east 
coast 
according to plan hallkimbrell also began diversifying in the 
late 1980s advising companies on environmental problems ranging 
from hazardous wastes and groundwater contamination 
next year it expects to start a hotline in connection with 
grocery store chains to let customers know how much pesticide is in 
the produce they buy 
the fast growth hasnt been problem free the company laid off 39 
workers earlier this summer in a move to cut costs 
earlier this year kimbrell had considered a 725 million buyout 
offer from law companies group an atlanta environmental firm but 
kimbrell said he rejected the deal because of differences with law 
companies over control 
nonetheless many analysts think such deals are the industrys 
future 
fastgrowing small to mediumsized companies such as 
hallkimbrell have dominated the asbestoscontrol business up to 
now but bigger environmental services companies are want a piece of 
the market now estimated between 1 billion and 3 billion a year 
said steven bernard a securities analyst with edward d jones amp co 
in st louis 
analysts foresee most of the industrys growth in the united 
states as more states approve even stricter asbestos guidelines for 
