<TEXT>
when the first 4minute mile was run it generated 
enthusiastic forecasts of a 3minute 50second mile to come when a 
highjumper achieved 8 feet sports enthusiasts said man could go 
higher 
same thing in stocks records create excitement and enthusiasm 
for more when the dow jones industrial average reached a new high 
last week you could hear the roar of the boosters seeking even 
greater heights 
it might work it might not 
excitement and enthusiasm have been ingredients of stock markets 
for all time and to some unmeasured degree they have an impact but 
when the cheering stops its the pace of the economy and profits 
that dictate prices 
the consensus forecast is for the economy to grow slowly just 
skirting recession the corporate profits outlook is for a loss of 
momentum a decline in the rate of growth it is happening already 
conceivably the stock market could see something the 
economists dont it wouldnt be the first time it has foreseen 
better or worse times than the consensus forecast it could happen 
again 
whatever the scaffolding for stock prices is stronger now than 
it was before the october 1987 crash when enthusiasm alone seemed 
to carry the market for several hundred points 
whether or not it is sufficiently strong is debatable 
wright investors service which relies on numerical rather than 
oratorical evidence of support advises a look at the profits 
picture specifically the slowing of the rate at which profits are 
rising 
with reports in from 90 percent of the companies making up the 
standard amp poors 500stock index secondquarter earnings are 
estimated to have risen only 5 percent from the same period a year 
ago thats hardly bullish 
that secondquarter performance appears even weaker when compared 
with the first quarters yearoveryear increase of 22 percent and 
with a 36 percent increase for the entire year 1988 vs 1987 
as measured by perhaps the most popular index of all the dow 
jones average of 30 industrial stocks the indications of support 
are no stronger compared with a year earlier secondquarter 
earnings of the 30 companies were down 5 percent 
many things move stock markets and percentages such as these are 
only one of them but theres one thing you can say about declines 
in profits or declines in the rate at which they are rising they 
cannot be ignored 
eventually stock prices and earnings must reconcile their 
differences they cannot go separate ways for long any more than 
the human heart and lungs can operate at their own individual tempos 
perhaps a better indication of the future might evolve from a 
government report due to be released this week the commerce 
departments estimate of real corporate profits 
wright believes the 7year bull market has had a sound basis for 
much of its life since operating profits excluding profits from 
priceinflated inventories and adjusted for depreciation did rise 
sustantially 
but it adds over the past three years operating profits havent 
been as impressive as they were earlier in the expansion in fact 
it says theyve been unimpressive and becoming more so 
it expects this weeks commerce department report to show signs 
of further profit deterioration 
</TEXT>
