<TEXT>
a hearing has been scheduled next month 
to determine whether former ohio financier marvin warner will be 
allowed to reorganize his financial affairs to stave off liquidation 
us bankruptcy judge george proctor scheduled a hearing sept 7 
on whether warners case should be converted back to a chapter 11 
reorganization instead of the chapter 7 liquidation decreed by the 
court july 28 
we hope at this hearing to present the true perspective of this 
case and unmask the nature of the claimants warner said following 
a hearing friday 
in his motion before the court the former us ambassador to 
switzerland who is appealing a securities conviction in ohio 
claimed he was not given proper advance notification of plans to 
convert the case to chapter 7 which allows the appointment of a 
trustee and liquidation of a debtors assets 
warner target of a flood of lawsuits following the collapse of 
his cincinnatibased home state savings bank in march 1985 said he 
filed for protection under chapter 11 of the us bankruptcy code in 
october 1987 in an attempt to consolidate the legal actions 
i came to chapter 11 not because i owed people money i wanted 
to consolidate in one forum these many lawsuits warner said 
friday 
he contends a list of creditors including the state of ohio 
seeking 45 billion are merely claimants 
i dont owe anybody anything warner said the attorney 
general of ohio has stated that the losses in the closing of home 
state have substantially been recovered how can the state of 
ohio justify having a claim of 275 million 
in march 1987 the creditors obtained a federal court order that 
warner pay back to ohio 22 million needed to guarantee home state 
deposits 
warner 70 was convicted on ohio felony charges in home states 
collapse but was acquitted of federal charges in a separate trial 
he is appealing the state conviction and a 22 million restitution 
order 
home state collapsed four days after esm government securities in 
fort lauderdale was shut down by federal regulators for insolvency 
home state had invested heavily with esm through securities trade 
and lost 144 million when esm was closed 
several months after the home state collapse warner and his wife 
jody moved from suburban cincinnati to a 153acre farm near ocala 
where warner breeds throughbred horses 
