<TEXT>
two soybean traders and a clerk pleaded guilty 
friday to charges of improper trading practices while 12 others 
pleaded innocent in the governments probe of alleged fraud at the 
worlds largest futures exchanges 
all those who appeared before us district judge william hart 
were involved in soybeantrading activity at the chicago board of 
trade during a 2year undercover probe by fbi agents masquerading 
as traders 
the four remaining soybean traders charged are to be arraigned 
sept 7 
a total of 45 traders and the clerk were indicted earlier this 
month after the investigation at the board of trade and the chicago 
mercantile exchange 
the three who pleaded guilty friday were freed on bond and have 
agreed to cooperate with the government in the remaining cases they 
most likely will testify against codefendants at upcoming trials 
said assistant us attorney sheila finnegan 
david skrodski 32 a soybean broker admitted that he defrauded 
customers by making prearranged trades in 1987 that he profited from 
with others charged in the alleged scheme he could be sentenced to 
a maximum of six years in prison and fined up to 350000 
craig lacrosse a 40yearold father of four admitted that he 
accepted an illegal prearranged trade from an undercover fbi agent 
posing as a trader in august 1988 he also admitted that he aided 
and abetted defendant james nowak accused of doctoring a trade to 
make it look as though lacrosse had been involved in the deal as a 
way to pay back money nowak owed lacrosse 
nowak was among the 12 soybean traders who pleaded innocent 
lacrosse also could face a maximum sixyear prison term and 
350000 fine 
