<DOCNO> AP890825-0251 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
federal reserve policymakers voted to nudge 
interest rates lower in july but they worried about reigniting 
inflation by going too far according to minutes of the meeting 
released friday 
the federal open market committee noting fairly consistent 
weakness in housing and consumer spending voted 101 at the end of 
its july 56 meeting to lower shortterm interest rates 
subsequently the benchmark federal funds rate the rate banks 
charge each other for overnight loans fell twice in quarterpoint 
increments to 9 percent 
it was the third crediteasing move by the central bank since 
early june after the federal funds rate hit a peak of more than 975 
percent the first loosening move had ended a yearlong program that 
increased the rate by three percentage points in an effort to 
squelch inflationary pressures 
however since last month the fed has held interest rates steady 
and the minutes indicate many members believed additional easing 
would be unwise in the absence of further indications of lagging 
economic growth 
many emphasized that current economic and financial 
uncertainties called for caution in adjusting policy at this 
point the minutes said in this view more than a slight move 
to less restraint could have an undesireable effect on inflationary 
expectations 
in the view of some members there remained some risk that 
inflationary pressures would intensify and that the easing might 
have to be reversed later the minutes said 
martha seger was the only committee member to dissent and h 
robert heller who earlier had announced his intention to resign 
from the fed was absent 
the minutes indicate seger believed the economy had slowed 
substantially and likely would weaken further next year unless 
the central bank pushed rates down more sharply than the majority 
decided 
the open market committee is composed of the seven federal 
reserve board governors and five of the 12 presidents of regional 
federal reserve banks it meets privately about eight times a year 
it aims to provide enough growth in the money supply to keep the 
economy out of a recession but also to avoid overheated growth that 
could accelerate inflation 
the committee issues directives that govern the open market desk 
of the federal reserve bank of new york through purchases or sales 
of government securities the fed influences the amount of money 
banks have available to make loans and thus the price of those 
loans interest rates 
the july directive to the new york bank in fed parlance was 
neutral the members decided that after the rate decline in 
july some firming or some easing would be acceptable 
depending on indications of inflationary pressures and the 
strength of the business expansion 
the open market committee met again on tuesday but minutes from 
that gathering wont be made public until three days after the next 
meeting on oct 3 
inflation has cooled recently but most analysts pointing to 
signs the economy may be rebounding from sluggishness in the first 
half believe the committee decided at its latest meeting to 
continue an evenhanded policy 
the unemployment rate dipped to 52 percent in july and retail 
sales rose 09 percent consumer prices rose at an annual rate of 
67 percent from january through may but fell to a little less than 
half of that in june and july as gasoline and food prices eased 
the july meeting also sets monetary targets for the rest of the 
year and preliminary targets for the following year the committee 
voted unanimously for a growth target this year of 3 percent to 7 
percent for a broad measure of the money supply that includes cash 
checking and savings accounts and money market mutual funds 
however the committee split 101 in recommending that the same 
target be maintained in 1990 breaking with the recent practice of 
reducing the target annually 
silas keehn president of the federal reserve bank of chicago 
dissented the minutes said because he believed a reduction of 
the ranges for the next year would provide an important signal of 
the feds continuing commitment to price stability 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

